               <floruit notBefore="1520" notAfter="1552">He was an Ethiopian monk renowned for his activity in <placeName ref="wd:Q220">Rome</placeName> at 
                  <placeName ref="INS0302SanStefano">Santo Stefano dei Mori</placeName> in <date>1536</date>.
                  He was the most learned medieval Ethiopian scholar and  an expert in Amharic, Gǝʿǝz, Arabic, Italian and Latin.  
                  He played a pivotal role in the two-year long preparation of one of the most important Ethiopic <ref type="work" corresp="LIT2463Testam">Testamentum Novum</ref> 
                  which was printed in two volumes. Very little is known about his career and education in <placeName ref="LOC3010Ethiop">Ethiopia</placeName>. 
                  But he was born from noble parents and his life was severely troubled by the Muslim wars waged by <persName ref="PRS1500Ahmad">ʾAḥmad</persName> 
                  against the Christian kingdom of Ethiopia. He spent a few years as a pilgrim in <placeName ref="wd:Q1218">Jerusalem</placeName> and then he moved to 
                  <placeName ref="wd:Q220">Rome</placeName> where he lived for 12 years.</floruit>
               <death notBefore="1550" notAfter="1552"/>
            </person>
            
